---
description: HARD RULES for documentation work. Fumadocs is the only docs framework. Lock to stable versions as of 2026-03-03. Headless primitives documentation standards enforced.
alwaysApply: true
---

# Scope
- Applies to ALL changes that touch documentation, docs tooling, or docs build output.
- If the user asks to change docs tooling, follow these rules unless the user explicitly overrides them.

# Version lock (as of 2026-03-03) — DO NOT CHANGE
- MUST pin and keep aligned:
  - fumadocs-core@16.6.8
  - fumadocs-ui@16.6.8
  - fumadocs-mdx@14.2.8
- MUST pin scaffolder:
  - create-fumadocs-app@16.0.63
- MUST NOT widen versions (no ^, no ~) for fumadocs packages unless user explicitly says “upgrade fumadocs”.
- MUST keep fumadocs-core and fumadocs-ui on the SAME version line.

# Fumadocs compatibility rules
- MUST treat Fumadocs packages as ESM-only.
- MUST NOT add CommonJS patterns (no require(), no module.exports) in docs code.

# Docs framework exclusivity
- MUST NOT add or scaffold other docs frameworks (Docusaurus, Nextra, VitePress, MkDocs, etc.).
- MUST NOT create a second docs site unless user explicitly asks.

# Source of truth rules
- MUST keep TypeScript source as the API source of truth.
- MUST prefer AutoTypeTable (or TypeTable) over manual type definitions.
- MUST NOT copy/paste large type definitions into docs pages.

# Change control rules
- MUST keep existing docs routing and folder layout.
- MUST NOT rename routes, move folders, or redesign navigation unless user explicitly asks.
- MUST keep changes minimal and focused on the requested task.

# Required doc page sections (for NEW primitive pages)
Every new page that documents a UI primitive, component, or hook MUST include these sections in this order:
1. Overview
2. API
3. Accessibility
4. Examples
5. Edge cases

Accessibility MUST include:
- Keyboard support
- Focus rules
- Screen reader notes
- Required roles/attributes/states
- Known limits

# Headless Primitive Documentation Standards (STRICT — MUST follow)
These rules apply to EVERY primitive page in addition to the required sections above.

## WHAT to document
Every primitive MUST cover:
- Anatomy (full list of sub-parts: Root, Trigger, Content, etc. + their roles/relationships)
- Controlled vs Uncontrolled behavior (default values, state management)
- Styling & Customization (all data-* attributes, className strategy, CSS variables, asChild support)
- Composition patterns (how to combine with other primitives, slotting, real-world usage)
- Installation & Import instructions
- Full API/Props (type-derived)
- Multiple real-world Examples
- Edge cases & Gotchas

## HOW to document using Fumadocs (as of 2026-03-03)
- **API section**: Use `<AutoTypeTable>` (preferred) or `<TypeTable>` for auto-generated type tables
- **Examples section**: Use `<Tabs>` (e.g. tabs for Basic / Controlled / Composition / Tailwind) with preview + code
- **Installation**: Use `<Steps>` component
- **Notes & warnings**: Use `<Callout type="info|warn|error">`
- Always show data attributes (`data-state=open`, `data-disabled`, etc.) in code examples
- Use Shiki-highlighted code blocks
- Keep examples practical, Tailwind-friendly, and composable — never assume a specific styling solution
- Import components from `fumadocs-ui/mdx` when needed

# Build safety
- MUST NOT claim tests/build ran unless you actually ran them.
- MUST warn clearly if a change could break docs build or docs routing.

# CRITICAL RULES (short)
- Do not change Fumadocs versions.
- Do not add other docs frameworks.
- Do not add CommonJS docs code.
- Do not change routes/layout without explicit user request.
- Always follow Headless Primitive Documentation Standards for every primitive.